<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION SELECT COMMITTEE (PASC)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC) and the Medical Research Council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (MRC)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">[</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">OD0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">16</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:7pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Publicly funded and collected data can have a significant value for economic growth, for health and for society more broadly. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Data openness, subject to appropriate safeguards, is an increasingly important issue in research. Data are key to evidence to inform public policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and should be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">openly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> available </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in an appropriate form</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> few restrictions as possible in a timely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">responsible manner.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A Government strategy on open data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can help to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure a co-ordinated and consistent approach to data collection, archiving and sharing across departments to address the trust, quality, value and confidentiality issues associated with data release. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Fora</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> uniting those engaged in open data and in producing Government statistics are valuable spaces to agree priorities and share information about the needs and requirements of specific stakeholder communities, though a strategic approach to engagement is needed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Resolving the complexities of open data in ways </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> realise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> potential without compromise to the rights of data subjects requires new access pathways and analysis techniques, as demonstrated by ongoing work associated with the Administrative Data Research Network.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Open data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> likely to be of interest to a wide range of audiences. Different users will have different requirements which need to be factored into how data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> presented, with data quality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> integrity, confidentiality and sustainability as overarching concerns.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government departments have a long-standing engagement with investment in UK data infrastructure and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research Councils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> hope to continue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> collaborative and mutually beneficial partnership with Government in this area.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Publicly funded and collected </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can have a significant value for economic growth, for health and for society more broadly. The Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC) and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Medical Research Council (MRC) are committed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the RCUK Common Principles on Data Policy</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which set out an overarching framework for individual research councils’ data policies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The RCUK principles </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recognise that publicly funded research data are a public good, produced in the public interest and should be made openly available with a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> few restrictions as possible in a timely and responsible manner.  Research data generated by research council funding must be discoverable, accessible and usable. In addition to funding research programmes which generate data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the research councils also support infrastructure, build capacity in key disciplines and deliver a policy framework for data sharing and preservation which ensure the research community and others can maximise the value of data.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For more than 40 years ESRC has been at the forefront of developing the UK’s social science data infrastructure, supporting the creation of world</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">leading data resources and major, pioneering data services which have played a leading and long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">standing role in shaping the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">international data landscape for social and economic research without compromise to the interests of data subjects. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MRC-funded researchers have made some of the most significant discoveries in medical science over 100 years — from identifying the link between smoking and cancer to the invention of therapeutic antibodies — benefiting millions of people in the UK and around the world. MRC investments in population studies, clinical trials, genomics and informatics are underpinning a period of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dramatic change in how patient data and research data can be used to inform better treatments, identify health risks and increase our understanding of the causes of disease. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ESRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and MRC collaborate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> closely with a wide range of stakeholders across Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including the UK health departments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and elsewhere who both produce and fund access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data resources for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> economic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and health research. For ESRC this include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> support and membership of the UK Data Forum (UKDF). The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">UK Strategy for Data Resources for Social and Economic Research 2013-2018</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> produced by the UKDF, provides a critical framework for identifying future data needs for the academic, policy and practitioner communities, including in response to the open data agenda. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Current MRC priorities in this area include increasing investments in health informatics and research involving patient data and capitalising on large</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scale population cohorts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ESRC and MRC welcome the opportunity to contribute to this inquiry. This submission is informed by our work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the focus is therefore on open data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that are used by research council funded scientists for social, economic and health research and increasing access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">research data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> generated by scientists funded by the research councils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:2pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:2pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why is open data important?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Open data, subject to appropriate safeguards, is an increasingly important issue in research: data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> key to evidence to inform public policy, and the drive to open up data is a major step towards providing a platform for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effective </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re-use of national and local data to facilitate research on public policy and service development. Open data is of value in understanding social</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> economic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and health </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changes in the UK, in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> providing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> evidenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">policies and in supporting efforts to drive forward the UK economy through improved and effective use of data.  Additionally, open data increases the accountability of Government to citizens through boosting transparency and accountability.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A number of recent reviews have addressed the benefits and potential of open data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> they each recognise and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">address the complexity of issues </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relating to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> openness, the legal and regulatory environment that governs the use of personal data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the resources needed to support access, both in relation to costs and expertise required to facilitate access.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2012 Royal Society Report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Science as an open enterprise</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">highlighted the enormous potential of open data for science and its application in public policy and business. Importantly the report also addressed the complex legal and regulatory environment that governs the use of personal data and introduced the concept of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘legitimate boundaries of openness’. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This concept was recently endorsed by Dame Fiona </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Caldicott’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Information Governance Review</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which investigated the balance between protecting patient information and sharing to improve patient care.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The review identifies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pseudonymised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and coded data as a ‘grey area’ and explores solutions that allows data linkage without putting confidentiality at risk. ESRC’s Secure Data Service was referenced as an example of securing the benefits of ‘open’ without increasing risk. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Shakespeare Review of Public Sector Information</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, published in May 2013, explored new ways of using public sector information to support economic growth and moved the agenda further forward. It places a duty on Government to make public sector information as open as possible, sharable and where practical free, to create maximum value. However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it also recognises that there are subsets of public sector information (such as research data, administrative data and health data) which cannot be fully open</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and endorses controlled and managed access so that privacy of individuals and confidentiality are maintained. It is noted that especially sensitive datasets should only be accessible to those who can demonstrate sufficient expertise in the area, potentially through accreditation.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As noted in the introduction above, the research councils are committed to the principle that publicly-funded data should be openly available to the maximum extent possible, this may include open-data publication or some form of managed access to ensure data are safe. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It is also important to ensure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data made open</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> used and re-used by suitably qualified, trained and experienced researchers as effectively as possible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; this is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in order to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">maintain the integrity of the data and to ensure the trust of research participants, both of which are essential to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">maximise its contribution to informing public policy and services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This is particularly important when bringing together data produced by different government departments or public bodies where individual’s identities may inadvertently be discoverable; thus suitable governance arrangements may need to considered to undertake cross-departmental analyses.</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ESRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and MRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">policy and practice demonstrates the importance we attach to open data in relation to the research we fund. The principles set out in the OECD report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Promoting access to public research data for scientific, economic and social development </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">underpin our data policy. Our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">policies</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> place great emphasis on data access and sharing, with clear expectations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for the researchers we fund</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">transparency and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the highest standards of ethics and integrity. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also support a number of data service providers who facilitate dissemination and promotion of existing data sources and provide easy, long-term access to those. Princip</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> among these is the UK Data Service (UKDS), based at the University of Essex.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UKDS holds data owned by national statistical authorities and UK Government departments, as well as intergovernmental organisations, research institutes and individual researchers. It offers a single point of controlled access to a wide range of secondary data including large-scale Government surveys, international </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">macrodata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, business </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">microdata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, qualitative studies, and census data from 1971 to 2011. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:7pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Open data is one part of a broader effort to maximise the contribution public data can make to the UK. Whilst most data can be shared quite straightforwardly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> –</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g. as it is appropriately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anonymised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more sensitive and require careful consideration of confidentiality, ethics, security and copyright issues when considering how best to make </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accessible. This is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">most likely to the case for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data generated through economic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and health </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">research and of the data such research may seek to analyse, such as administrative or other publicly funded data.  It is important that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s strategy for open data allows for managed access through sharing and safe havens and that it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is not deterred from making data it holds available because it is not yet suited to unrestricted access. Significant additional value can be derived from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> made available to a particular community of users or for a specific research purpose. An example of such an approach to administrative data is outlined below.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition, public views of open data and its value are important and complex. Research Councils UK (RCUK), in partnership with JISC, the Royal Society and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sciencewise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-ERC, commissioned a public dialogue to provide insight into issues around data openness, re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use and management technologies to inform future policies. The findings, published in June 2012</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, show that, though supportive in principle, the public have a nuanced view about data openness. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ccording to the consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he extent to which data should be made available depends on the funder of research and public interest in the topic. Openness is also perceived as needing to be balanced with costs (which include the time of researchers). The principal benefits of open data are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">seen to accrue for researchers rather than the public, with participants more interested in the results and implications of the research than personally exploring datasets.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why does the Government need an open data strategy?</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The importance of open data to the UK is clear. Much work has already been done on setting out priorities and strategies in relation to this, for example through, and in response to, the transparency agenda and the Shakespeare Review. A Government strategy on open data provides a critical guiding framework to ensure that the ambitions for, and potential of, open data are realised by promoting a co-ordinated and consistent approach to data collection, archiving and sharing. Such a strategic  approach: </span></li></ol><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">avoids duplication of effort </span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">makes access and re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use by the public easier</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">creates opportunities for harmonisation</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enables comparability across datasets for research purposes</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">maximises the use of existing and emerging mechanisms that facilitate access</span></li></ul><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improves performance through increased  transparency and accountability</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">addresses public concern over privacy and data security issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The digital revolution means more Government data than ever before </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> being collected and stored electronically, opening up new opportunities for releasing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use. However, it is important that data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> collected and shared in a way that enables and encourages this. Usability and discoverability are core to any success. The Departmental Open Data Strategies have been a welcome first step, as are the improvements made to data.gov.uk. Researchers now know what data they can expect to be made available and have a portal they can use to access it. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Coalition Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s strategic approach to open data and transparency provides the opportunity for harmonisation around data access and re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use and enables greater consistency in the ways in which data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> made available by public bodies, the metadata associated with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the user support available. Common sets of standards increase usability. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In future</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, greater collaboration between Government departments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in sharing data should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lead to improved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">greater confidence in government data (as findings in one data set are supported or challenged by another through systematic comparison) and new understanding (as data from different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anonymised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sources are combined responsibly)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will also be collected in such a way that will reduce the processing required to release the data while maintaining public confidence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Greater consistency across Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also allow users to take advantage of new technical tools to re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use the data. The most obvious example here is APIs (Application Programming Interfaces) that are able to re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">present or re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use data in new ways for both the public good and to inform businesses, as used for example in data.gov.uk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and in the RCUK Gateway to Research</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As highlighted above, open data principles cannot be implemented in an undifferentiated way, given the complex nature of the issues raised. A Government strategy ensures that, as increasing volumes of data are potentially made available for access, appropriate practical mechanisms and underlying principles are put in place. This is essential to ensure that data and the way access is provided meet the trust, quality, value and confidentiality concerns associated with open data. This ensures a coherent and coordinated response across Government, with departmental strategies applying the overall strategy in specific contexts. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can those engaged in open data, and those engaged in producing Government statistics work together effectively to produce new data?</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The development of a shared approach between those who are engaged in open data and those producing Government statistics is essential to the successful generation of new, accessible data that respects the rights of data subjects. As highlighted above, a common set of standards across Government is critical to avoiding duplication of effort, promoting shared practice, increasing usability and comparability, and reducing the processing needed to release data while maintaining the highest standards of research ethics and integrity. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Partnership mechanisms, which include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fora</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> such as the UK Data Forum (UKDF), are valuable spaces in which priorities can be agreed and information shared about the needs and requirements of specific stakeholder communities. The Open Data Institute is another example of efforts to bring together experts in open data from different perspectives to collaborate and promote innovation and new ideas.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  It is important that these receive appropriate engagement and have a clear role to play if they are to be effective. In addition, in such a busy and fast-moving landscape</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it is important to avoid the proliferation of multiple </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fora</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. A joined</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">up and strategic approach to engagement is essential.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">International standards are also a useful foundation around which to build shared measures and practices in relation to open data, and work to develop, monitor and respond to these should be undertaken. An OECD Global Science Forum expert group on international data recently recommended the development of agreed and common standards for the documentation of data collection and processing, and enhanced harmonisation of social and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">economic data across statistical and other agencies.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">UK Strategy for Data Resources for Social and Economic Research, 2013-2018</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> advocates support for these actions, and UKDF is establishing links to data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in other countries, particularly in the EU. Engaging with the development of international standards, and creating mechanisms to promote their application across Government, will contribute to effective collaborative working. The commitment to maintaining the highest standards of research ethics and integrity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK is key to realising the potential of international data.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can more statistics and administrative data of all kinds become more freely available?</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One form of data of particular relevance to Government is administrative data, whose analysis offers enormous potential to inform social scientific research as well as to benefit society in the ways outlined in recent reports. However, openness in relation to administrative data is not straightforward. There is a need to balance its release with measures to ensure that, where appropriate, access is mediated in order to minimise the risk of disclosure. There is a need to consider how the various administrative data should become more available and particularly how this can be done safely. Methods and practices need to be harmonised and developed to make administrative data as open as possible without either requiring the removal of so much detail that the data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> useless for research or risk breaching data protection rights.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ESRC’s Big Data Network is developing innovative investments to strengthen the UK’s comparative advantage in Big Data, including in relation to administrative data, and to develop new pathways to access and new analytical techniques to facilitate high quality research. Phase </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one of the Big Data Network </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is focusing on administrative data, an area of central importance to the ESRC in recent years. The Administrative Data Taskforce (ADT), chaired by Sir Alan </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Langlands</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, saw the ESRC and other partners promote better use of such data and the removal of barriers to this. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ADT Report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘Improving Access for Research and Policy’</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, published in December 2012, recommended a framework to facilitate research based on linked administrative data – the Administrative Data Research Network (ADRN) – which is in the process of being established by the ESRC, in partnership with Government.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ADRN will provide a robust infrastructure for accessing and linking administrative data under a single governance structure that will allow for consistent and robust decision-making. The combination of a coordinating administrative data service and four data research </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will help position the UK at the forefront of research based on administrative data. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ADRN will seek to facilitate and support access to administrative data in a secure setting. The model builds on existing settings in Government, such as the Virtual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Microdata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Laboratory within the ONS</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the HMRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Datalab</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but also the ESRC-funded Secure Data Service (SDS)</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The SDS was set up to enable safe and secure remote access by researchers to data previously deemed too sensitive, detailed, confidential or potentially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disclosive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to be made available under standard licensing and dissemination arrangements and the service has been integrated into the work of the UK Data Service. As the ADRNs activity progresses it will be important that the ADRN work closely with the newly funded Farr Institute for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ealth </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nformatics </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">esearch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Farr Institute is supported by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ten</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> partners, including ERSC and the MRC and is coordinated by the MRC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The second phase </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ESRC’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Big Data Network will focus primarily on business data and local government data, with a series of Data Research </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> being currently commissioned to deliver the infrastructure to support access to these forms of data.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Phase </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">three</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, further details of which will be released this autumn, will focus primarily on third sector data and social media data.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is open data presented well and of adequate quality?</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Different data will be of interest to a wide range of users, including the public, media, the third sector and businesses, as well as researchers, who will have different requirements of open data that will impact on how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> best presented to meet their needs. To ensure the greatest value</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> specialist data need to presented in ways that are accessible, informative, engaging, honest and which allow a safe range of non-expert interpretation and insight. There are similar risks t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> limiting the value of data within large, complex tables</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and data custodians must find creative ways of presenting data and information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. ‘P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">olice.uk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is a good example of creative presentation which demonstrates the success alternative formats can have. Specialised and complex datasets can be difficult for non-experts to use and faulty analysis could be damaging to the public interest, for example complex health data can be interpreted in several ways, some of which may be harmful such as the analysis of benefits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> harms of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MMR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> vaccine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the 1990s. New users of complex data may benefit from expert assistance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n considering how data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> best presented, balancing the needs and interests of different user groups requires careful consideration: one size will not fit all.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Data quality is a critical issue regardless of how data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> presented, both for those who wish to access data directly, such as researchers, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> those who may be more interested in the results and implications of its analysis, such as the public and policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">makers. High quality metadata is essential, particularly where the data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not generated or compiled for research purposes. The quality of subsequent analysis and data generated by new research is also important</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> data creators would expect that new uses and new users are as stringent as they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> creators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have been. As discussed above, there is a drive to standardise the documentation that accompanies data internationally, and various standards are in place that are commonly acknowledged to be best practice.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The quality of data archiving and active </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">curation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  important to ensure that data  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accessible and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> presented and preserved in ways that ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> continue to be useable in comparable and robust ways in the future. Data collection and preservation methods vary across time, and continue to evolve in line with technological advances and the development of standards. Sustainability is therefore a significant concern in considering appropriate ways to preserve and archive open data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this is a particular concern for data assets that inform policy decisions and which have long-term value.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How successful has the Government’s Open Data initiative been in changing behaviour in the Civil Service and wider public sector?</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government Departments have had a long-standing engagement with investment in the UK data infrastructure. The UKDF includes representatives from a variety of Departments, and other ESRC data infrastructure investments that have seen department involvement include the Administrative Data Liaison Service (ADLS) and our longitudinal studies. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition, through support and participation in the ADT in the last two years, Departments have committed resource to work together to actively seek solutions to making more administrative data available. There has been additional resource committed within Departments to ensure that progress is made, as well as investment in Departmental infrastructure such as the expansion of the HMRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Datalab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This on-going contribution and involvement has been highly valuable. The ESRC is encouraged by the support and response to its initiatives by Government and hopes to continue this collaborative and mutually beneficial partnership. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Which datasets are the most important?</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Social scientists have used a wide range of survey datasets, as demonstrated by the most popular datasets accessed through the UKDS. These include Government-produced datasets such as the Quarterly Labour Force Surveys, the Health Survey for England, and the British Crime Survey, as well as those produced through ESRC investments, such as the British Household Panel Survey and Understanding Society, and others such as the English Longitudinal Study of Ageing.  The challenge is now to make greater use of administrative data and link where appropriate to this survey data.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> answer this question in detail could in itself easily be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the subject of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a consultation given the breadth of data and diversity of potential use. However, one example that demonstrates well the value of opening up of Government data is the availability of Ordnance Survey data. This, alongside other initiatives such as UK Location, has enabled growth in the linking of datasets to geographical locations in an increasingly standardised way while respecting the rights of data subjects.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How effective is the work being undertaken by the Cabinet Office to monitor the progress of Departments in publishing their agreed datasets?</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is not a question the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">research councils are well</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> placed to answer, although the ESRC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and MRC, through RCUK, are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> participating in the relevant transparency boards and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> engaging with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">epartments as they develop their approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the open data agenda. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.rcuk.ac.uk/research/Pages/DataPolicy.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.rcuk.ac.uk/research/Pages/DataPolicy.aspx</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.esrc.ac.uk/_images/UK%20Data%20forum%20strategy_tcm8-28338.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.esrc.ac.uk/_images/UK%20Data%20forum%20strategy_tcm8-28338.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://royalsociety.org/policy/projects/science-public-enterprise/report/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://royalsociety.org/policy/projects/science-public-enterprise/report/</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://caldicott2.dh.gov.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://caldicott2.dh.gov.uk/</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; fon